explanations for its longevity, Defoe’s tour de force has been interpreted as both religious allegory and frontier myth, its hero viewed variously as the self-sufficient adventurer and the archetypal colonizer and capitalist. Defoe’s original has been reimagined multiple times in legions of Robinsonade or castaway stories, but there is still more to say—the Crusoe myth is far from spent. The contributors to this wide-ranging collection suggest new and unfamiliar ways of thinking about this most familiar of works, asking us to consider the enduring appeal of “Crusoe", more recognizable today than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCrusoe, Defoe, castaway, myth, icon, Robinson Crusoe, 1650, 1850, Robinsonade, Transgender Voyage, Burlesquing Crusoe, Anthropomorphism, Identification in Children’s Robinsonades, Tobacco Rites, Children’s Robinsonades, 1719, desert island, animal castaways.1 aBrown, Laura Schafer.1 aBrown, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Jeremy.1 aHicks, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHicks, Amy.1 aMueller, Andreas K E, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMueller, Andreas K E.1 aMueller, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, Maximillian E.1 aNovak, Maximillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauley, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauley, Benjamin.1 aPyrz, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPyrz, Scott.1 aRidley, Glynis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c